The Asian Development Bank warned of a potential epidemic in China due to tainted food affecting 300 million people annually.
The lack of food safety laws poses a threat to public health and the economy.
The government initiated a food safety evaluation campaign in major cities to address concerns.
Calls for a unified supervision mechanism and stricter punishments for offenders were made to prevent future incidents.
Recent food safety scandals have raised public alarm, prompting the implementation of fast testing systems and stricter regulations.
China aims to enhance monitoring and enforcement to ensure food and drug safety over the next five years.
